''955''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''[[United States presidential election in New York, 1904|1904]]'''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''64.0%''' ''10,182''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|30.9% ''4,923''\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|5.1% ''814''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''[[United States presidential election in New York, 1900|1900]]'''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''59.5%''' ''9,948''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|37.2% ''6,224''\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|3.2% ''541''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''[[United States presidential election in New York, 1896|1896]]'''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''58.8%''' ''9,337''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|38.3% ''6,088''\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|2.9% ''464''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''[[United States presidential election in New York, 1892|1892]]'''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''52.8%''' ''7,973''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|38.1% ''5,753''\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|9.1% ''1,379''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''[[United States presidential election in New York, 1888|1888]]'''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''54.6%''' ''8,586''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|39.2% ''6,173''\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|6.2% ''975''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''[[United States presidential election in New York, 1884|1884]]'''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''50.3%''' ''7,463''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|40.9% ''6,065''\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|8.8% ''1,302''\n|}\n{{Hidden end}}\n\nCattaraugus County is run by a [[unicameral legislature]] who appoint a county \"administrator.\" This individual serves many executive duties of a county executive but has no legislative veto power and is not elected.\n\nThe legislators are elected independently by districts (while some also serve as mayors of the villages they represent, their status as mayors does not affect in any way their seats on the legislature and thus it is not a [[Board of Supervisors]]). The county uses a system of [[proportional representation]] in which each legislator's vote is weighted to the number of persons in their district; each district can have between one and three legislators. This system was imposed in the 1960s in the wake of the [[one man, one vote]] federal court rulings of the era; prior to this, the county operated under a true board of supervisors model. There are currently 21 members of the legislature with 15 Republicans and 6 Democrats; the county is in the process of reducing that number to 17. Each legislator serves a four-year term, with a limit of three terms.\n\nA majority of the county council are Republicans, and only two years in the entire history of the county legislature (1992 to 1994) have seen the Democrats in the majority.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oleantimesherald.com/news/longtime-cattaraugus-county-legislator-joseph-k-eade-dies/article_ec217d20-3553-11e8-baa1-3f3613d09623.html|title=Longtime Cattaraugus County legislator Joseph K. Eade dies|first=RICK MILLER, Olean Times|last=Herald|date=|website=oleantimesherald.com}}</ref> Norman L. Marsh of Little Valley serves as Chairman, and James J. Snyder of Olean serves as Vice-Chairman.\n* 01 - one seat\n* 02 - Richard L. Klancer (R) and Patrick J. Murphy (R)\n* 03 - Norman L. Marsh (R) and Howard VanRensselaer (R)\n* 04 - William E. Sprague (D)\n* 05 - Donna Vickman (R), Gary M. Felton (R) and William H. Weller (R)\n* 06 - James J. Snyder Jr. (R) and Dan M. Hale (R)\n* 07 - James L. Boser (D) and Richard J. Lamberson (D)\n* 08 - Carl W. Edwards (R)\n* 09 - David M. Koch (D) and Susan Labuhn (R)\n* 10 - John J. Padlo (D), Linda M. Edstrom (R), James J. Snyder (R), Earl B. McElfresh (R) and Steven Teachman (R)\n\nCattaraugus County is entirely within the boundaries of the 148th [[New York State Assembly]] District (served currently by [[Joseph Giglio]]), the 57th [[New York State Senate]] District (served currently by [[Catharine Young]]), and the [[U.S. House of Representatives]] [[New York's 29th congressional district|29th district]] (served currently by [[Tom Reed (politician)|Tom Reed]]). In the last of these, Cattaraugus County's votes proved pivotal in the 2008 elections: incumbent Republican [[Randy Kuhl]], who had strongly carried the county in 2004 and 2006, lost Cattaraugus County to Democrat [[Eric Massa]] in the 2008 elections.\n\nThe county is generally considered a \u201cred county,\u201d with Republicans usually outvoting Democrats in most statewide and national offices (for instance, in 2004 [[George W. Bush]] defeated [[John Kerry]] in Cattaraugus County by a 60\u201340 margin) although [[Bill Clinton]] won Cattaraugus County very narrowly in 1996. In 2006, the county narrowly chose [[Eliot Spitzer]] over [[John Faso]] by a margin of about 1 percent in [[New York gubernatorial election, 2006|the governor's race]], and [[Hillary Clinton]] defeated [[John Spencer (mayor)|John Spencer]] in the county by a 10 percentage point margin. (That being said, in all other positions up for office that year, Republicans won\u2014including all congressional and state legislature representatives.)\n\nIn 2008 the county voted for the Republican presidential candidate, with [[John McCain]] defeating [[Barack Obama]] by a 55-44% margin. In 2010, Republican [[Carl Paladino]] carried Cattaraugus County over Democrat (and eventual winner) [[Andrew Cuomo]] 65% to 31%. Senator [[Kirsten Gillibrand]] and Senator [[Chuck Schumer]], both incumbent Democrats, carried the county by 51% to 46% and 54% to 43% margins, respectively. Despite largely being a non-factor in heavily Democratic New York's statewide elections, the county regularly has unusually high turnout for Presidential elections, with upwards of 70 percent of eligible voters typically voting in the county.\n\nAn emerging trend among Cattaraugus County's villages has been consolidation with their surrounding towns. [[Limestone, New York|Limestone]] voters approved dissolution into the [[Carrollton, New York|Town of Carrollton]] in September 2009; that took effect at the beginning of 2011. On March 18, 2010, three other villages ([[East Randolph, New York|East Randolph]], [[Randolph (CDP), New York|Randolph]] and [[Perrysburg (CDP), New York|Perrysburg]]) followed suit and approved dissolution into their surrounding towns ([[Randolph (town), New York|Town of Randolph]] for the first two, and [[Perrysburg (town), New York|Town of Perrysburg]] for the third); these three villages dissolved at the beginning of 2012.\n\n==Additional facts==\nTwo geological formations, both called \"Rock City,\" have the appearance of a town laid out with streets. One is in [[Olean (town), New York|Olean]] and the other is in [[Little Valley (town), New York|Little Valley]].\n\n[[Olean (city), New York|Olean]] is the largest city in the county and is the major center for business. [[Ski country]] runs through Cattaraugus County; two ski resorts, popular with Canadians, lie in the town of [[Ellicottville (town), New York|Ellicottville]]: [[Holiday Valley Resort]] and HoliMont; Cattaraugus County once had numerous ski resorts within its bounds, scattered throughout the county, before contracting into Ellicottville alone by 1980. In addition, several snowmobile trails cross the county, including the [[Pat McGee Trail]], a flagship for the county's trail system, and the [[North Country Trail]].\n\nCattaraugus County's current promotional nickname is the ''Enchanted Mountains.'' The county's heights are mostly described as hills; it has only two comparatively small \"mountains\" (Mount Seneca and Mount Tuscarora, both in [[Allegany State Park]]). During the 1980s, the county used the slogan ''Naturally Yours to Enjoy.''\n\nCattaraugus County is considered part of [[Appalachia]], as well as [[Western New York]], [[upstate New York]], the [[Southern Tier]], the [[Twin Tiers]] and the [[Buffalo-Niagara Falls metropolitan area|Buffalo-Niagara-Cattaraugus Combined Statistical Area]]. As a result of being at a geographic crossroads, the people of Cattaraugus County speak a variety of accents, ranging from mild variants of [[Appalachian English]] to [[Inland Northern American English]], with a handful of people speaking in the more loud and nasal [[Buffalo English]].\n\nThe sales tax in Cattaraugus County is 8% (4% from New York, 4% from the county).\n\nA large [[Amish]] community is located in the western part of the county; with an estimated 2,500 residents, they constitute slightly under 3% of the county's population.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.oleantimesherald.com/olean/health-officials-worry-about-cattaraugus-county-s-amish-amidst-u/article_ff2d5d95-b875-5c95-bcf3-b156b70c522a.html|title=Health officials worry about Cattaraugus County's Amish amidst U.S. measles outbreak|first=RICK MILLER Olean Times|last=Herald|website=Olean Times Herald|accessdate=Jan 30, 2020}}</ref> A portion of this community maintains an exceptionally older order that eschews indoor plumbing, which, combined with a small number of Seneca who still live on traditional subsistence, gives the county a high rate of homes without indoor plumbing compared to nearby counties.<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/wonkblog/wp/2014/04/23/1-6-million-americans-dont-have-indoor-plumbing-heres-where-they-live/?Post+generic=%3Ftid%3Dsm_twitter_washingtonpost \"1.6 million Americans don't have indoor plumbing. Here's where they live\"], ''The Washington Post''. Retrieved April 24, 2014.</ref>\n\n==Media==\n\n===Newspapers===\n* ''[[Salamanca Press]]'' (weekly, serving Salamanca and a few other small towns)\n* ''[[Olean Times Herald]]'' (daily, serving all of the western [[Twin Tiers]])\n* ''Olean Source'' (free weekly)\n* ''Franklinville Mercury-Gazette'' (free weekly)\n* ''Ellicottville Time''s (free weekly, based in Ellicottville)\n* ''The Villager'' (free weekly, based in Ellicottville)\n* ''Randolph Register'' (monthly)\n* ''Ellicottville Snowed In'' / ''The Summer Local'' (monthly)\n* ''Gowanda Press'' (weekly, published out of Salamanca)\n* ''Gowanda\u2014Silver Creek Pennysaver'' (weekly, published out of Fredonia)\n* ''Pennysaver News'' (weekly, published by ''[[The Buffalo News]]'', which is also distributed throughout the county)\n\n===Radio stations===\n* [[WPIG]] (95.7, Olean)\n* [[WOLY (AM)|WOLY]] (1450, translator on 107.1, Olean)\n* [[WBFO|WOLN]] (91.3, Olean, operated out of Buffalo)\n* [[WQRS]] (98.3, Salamanca, operated out of Olean, transmitter in Carrollton)\n* [[WGGO]] (1590, Salamanca, operations and transmitter in Kill Buck)\n* [[WGWE]] (105.9, Little Valley, operated from the Allegany Reservation)\n* [[WOEN]] (1360, Olean)\n* [[WMXO]] (101.5, Olean) \n* [[WSBU]] (88.3, St. Bonaventure) \n* [[WAGL (FM)|WAGL]] (96.7, Portville, operated out of Olean)\n* [[WTWT]] (90.5, transmitter in Allegany, licensed to Bradford, PA, operated out of Russell, PA)\n* [[WWG32]] (162.425, Little Valley, operated out of Buffalo)\n\n===Television stations===\n* [[WWHC-LP]] (Ch. 20, Olean)\n* [[WVTT-CD]] (Ch. 25, licensed to Olean, transmitter on Machias/Yorkshire town line)\n* [[W30BW]] (Ch. 30, licensed to Olean, transmitter on the Freedom town line)\n\n==Education==\nA branch of [[Jamestown Community College]], in [[Olean (city), New York|Olean]] provides higher education for residents.  [[Olean Business Institute]] provided specialized education and is also in Olean; it closed in 2013 due to financial and enrollment declines. [[Jamestown Business College]] operates a satellite campus in Salamanca. [[Cornplanter College]], a [[tribally controlled college]], opened in 2014 in Salamanca.  [[St. Bonaventure University]] is located in [[Saint Bonaventure, New York|its own census-designated place]] just west of Olean.\n\n==Communities==\n[[File:Cattaraugus County, New York Divisions.png|thumb|350px|right|Cattaraugus County divisions]]\n\n===Cities===\n* [[Olean, New York|Olean]]\n* [[Salamanca (city), New York|Salamanca]]\n\n===Towns===\n{{Div col|colwidth=12em}}\n* [[Allegany (town), New York|Allegany]]\n* [[Ashford, New York|Ashford]]\n* [[Carrollton, New York|Carrollton]]\n* [[Coldspring, New York|Coldspring]]\n* [[Conewango, New York|Conewango]]\n* [[Dayton, New York|Dayton]]\n* [[East Otto, New York|East Otto]]\n* <s>[[Elko, New York|Elko]]</s> ''(dissolved 1965)''\n* [[Ellicottville, New York|Ellicottville]]\n* [[Farmersville, New York|Farmersville]]\n* [[Franklinville (town), New York|Franklinville]]\n* [[Freedom, New York|Freedom]]\n* [[Great Valley, New York|Great Valley]]\n* [[Hinsdale, New York|Hinsdale]]\n* [[Humphrey, New York|Humphrey]]\n* [[Ischua, New York|Ischua]]\n* [[Leon, New York|Leon]]\n* [[Little Valley, New York|Little Valley]]\n* [[Lyndon, New York|Lyndon]]\n* [[Machias, New York|Machias]]\n* [[Mansfield, New York|Mansfield]]\n* [[Napoli, New York|Napoli]]\n* [[New Albion, New York|New Albion]]\n* [[Olean (town), New York|Olean]]\n* [[Otto, New York|Otto]]\n* [[Perrysburg (town), New York|Perrysburg]]\n* [[Persia, New York|Persia]]\n* [[Portville, New York|Portville]]\n* [[Randolph, New York|Randolph]]\n* [[Red House, New York|Red House]]\n* [[Salamanca (town), New York|Salamanca]]\n* [[South Valley, New York|South Valley]]\n* [[Yorkshire (town), New York|Yorkshire]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Villages===\n{{